<br>
If prisons were a place for punishment instead of failed attempts at rehabilitation, there wouldn't be a need for death as another supposed deterrant.<br>
<br>
As for DNA, you'll never hear testimony that says DNA proves 100% without a doubt that someone &quot;belongs&quot; to whatever DNA evidence presented, it merely reduces the number of possibilities.  In some cases that's close enough, but there was an interesting story on one of those A&amp;E crime shows a while back.  A man from a very small town (population around 500 and dropping) was commited of a murder in a larger nearby city.  He was convicted based on a witness description and DNA evidence.  On appeal, his lawyer did some checking and found something scary.  The town had been so heavily inbred several generations back that about 10 other men had identical DNA profiles and matched his basic physical description.  They ended up testing the entire town to check the accuracy of the results, and everyone who's family had lived in the town for 3 generations shared enough DNA to match as an immediate family relation. <p><img src=http://www.kaseyspace.com/EQ/nenasig.jpg align=center>
